<details class="individual" name="element" markdown>
  <summary>
  <div class="overview">
    <div class="label">
      <h3 id="cr-s4_i">To limit authorsâ€™ ability to interpret and develop the language by binding it to past usage is akin to denying the contemporary Church its role in interpreting and expanding upon sacred Scripture.</h3>
      <a class="individual" href="#cr-s4_i">https://w3id.org/contro/caro-castelvetro#cr-s4</a>
    </div>
  <ul>
    <h4>Class</h4>

      <a class="class" href="https://w3id.org/contro/arg#Statement" title="https://w3id.org/contro/arg#Statement">Statement</a><span class="sup" data-text="c" title="Class"></span>
    </li>
  </ul>
  </div>
  </summary>
  <div class="extra">
    <ul>
      <h4>Assertions</h4>
      <li>
        <a class="object_property" href="https://w3id.org/contro/arg#contradicts" title="https://w3id.org/contro/arg#contradicts">contradicts</a><span class="sup" data-text="op" title="Object Property"></span> <a class="individual" href="#cv-s5_i" title="https://w3id.org/contro/caro-castelvetro#cv-s5">In the context of Petrarchist poetry, authors should not use words that Petrarch himself chose not to use.</a><span class="sup" data-text="i" title="Individual"></span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <a class="data_property" href="http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#value" title="http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#value">value</a><span class="sup" data-text="dp" title="Data Property"></span> This is to hold in matters of language the very same belief one holds in matters of faith: to claim that vernacular Italian should be confined to Petrarch and Boccaccio, just as to claim that sacred Scripture is wholly contained in the Gospels and Saint Paul.
